    parentName: "p"
  }, "Classic"), " - which Android supports majestically, but Apple (un-shockingly) has their on proprietary nonsense called ", mdx("strong", {
    parentName: "p"
  }, "MFi"), " that requires vendors to jump through a bunch of hoops in designing hardware. Which is pretty mind boggling since BLE is available without much issue - what's so specially about classic? Except Apple being Apple. Back to the library hunt - there were a number of libraries accessing Bluetooth classic on Android but literally zero on IOS. Was my decision to choose React Native a terrible one? Initially it looked like it, but after continuing to look around it seemed like there were no real libraries for use on IOS to communicate with Bluetooth classic anyhow - thankfully this meant that no matter what choice I made, I was going to need to write my own communication library."), mdx("p", null, "Thankfully our hardware vendors were super great with their knowledge and information which made the process easy. Read more about my ", mdx("a", {
